thread.title: Columbia River coho returns aren’t living up to expectations
thread.title_full: Columbia River coho returns aren’t living up to expectations | The Seattle Times

author: Mark Yuasa
title: Columbia River coho returns aren’t living up to expectations
text:
While the Columbia River fall chinook return appears to be the second largest on record it looks like their coho brothers are taking a hit.
“The coho returns aren’t like we expected, and not so favorable,” said Joe Hymer, a state Fish and Wildlife biologist. “I looked at data (on Tuesday) and the lower river return are about seven percent compared to last year. The jack coho return is about half of last year, and counts are down at Bonneville Dam.”
Here is a list that breakdowns how coho are faring at this point.
Hatchery adult coho returns to Washington lower Columbia river stations are less than 10% of the same time last year:

Toutle 116 175 Early stock. 
Cowlitz 571 15,288 Late stock. Includes integrated wild and hatchery stocks. 
Kalama 74 1,262 Early stock. 917 adults counted at new Modrow trap this year. 
Lewis 1,802 19,490 Early stock. 
Total 2,563 36,215 7%

Hatchery jack coho returns are slightly more than half the same time last year: 
Toutle 2 17 Early stock. 
Cowlitz 735 1,398 Late stock. Includes integrated wild and hatchery stocks. 
Kalama 1 130 Early stock. 9 jacks counted at new Modrow trap this year. 
Lewis 1,040 1,736 Early stock.

Total 1,778 3,281 54% 
 
Bonneville Dam counts of early stock adult and jack coho are also way down from the same time last year (thru Sept. 30):

Adults 26,917 181,514 15% 
Jacks 3,594 10,254 35% 
Even worse for late stock coho from Oct. 1-12: 
Adults 2,618 36,435 7% 
Jacks 496 2,518 20%
